      <title type="html"><![CDATA[$\rm \LaTeX$ Template for Essays]]></title>
      <link href="https://vincenttam.github.io/blog/2014/03/16/latex-template-for-essays/"/>
    
    <updated>2014-03-16T00:28:20+08:00</updated>
    <id>https://vincenttam.github.io/blog/2014/03/16/latex-template-for-essays</id>
    
      <content type="html"><![CDATA[<h2 id="introduction">Introduction</h2>

<p>This is a $\rm \LaTeX$ template for writing an article.</p>

<h2 id="sample-output">Sample output</h2>

<p><a href="/downloads/latex-sample.pdf">Click here.</a></p>

<!-- more -->

<h2 id="sample-code">Sample code</h2>

<p><div><script src='https://gist.github.com/9569005.js'></script>
<noscript><pre><code>@online{Gnu13,
  author = {Richard Stallman},
  title = {{Free Software and Education}},
  date = {2013-11-06},
  url = {http://www.gnu.org/education/education.html}
}

@article{kaplan2010users,
  title={{Users of the world, unite! The challenges and opportunities
    of social media}},
  author={Kaplan, Andreas M and Haenlein, Michael},
  journal={{Business Horizons}},
  volume={53},
  number={1},
  pages={59--68},
  year={2010},
  publisher={Elsevier}
}
</code></pre></noscript></div>
</p>

<h2 id="explanation-of-code-in-latex-sampletex">Explanation of code in “latex-sample.tex”</h2>

<p>For the one-inch margin, I have used the geometry package to do so.
(line 2) The font size has been set to 12. (line 1) The 1.5 line
spacing has been implemented. (lines 7–8)</p>

<p>The APA-style reference list was automatically generated using the
biblatex package along with the biber backend. (lines 15–17,107)</p>

<h2 id="comparison-of-rm-latex-and-other-technologies">Comparison of $\rm \LaTeX$ and other technologies</h2>

<p>I personally appreciate the beauty of Professor Donald Knuff’s
Computer Modern typefaces, and thus the font Computer Modern Roman has
been chosen through the whole PDF file.  In terms the number of
trailing hyphenations in each line, and other relating in-word spacing
statistics, $\rm \LaTeX$ is better than an array of
internationally-acclaimed proprietary softwares, such as Microsoft
Word and Abode InDesign<sup id="fnref:1"><a href="#fn:1" class="footnote">1</a></sup>.  In addition, the typesetting of
Microsoft is incorrect, whereas $\rm \LaTeX$ gives the correct kerning
and ligatures of characters, apart from rendering “ancient and rare
ligatures”<sup id="fnref:2"><a href="#fn:2" class="footnote">2</a></sup>.  The staff in the Department of Engineering at the
University of Cambridge has made a more comprehensive and detailed
comparison of WYSIWYG (What-You-See-Is-What-You-Get) editors and $\rm
\LaTeX$ <a href="http://www.eng.cam.ac.uk/help/tpl/textprocessing/latex_advocacy.html">here</a>.</p>

<hr />

<p>I’ve found <a href="http://latex.informatik.uni-halle.de/latex-online/latex.php">$\rm \LaTeX$-Online-Compiler</a>, which is useful
for testing $\rm \LaTeX$ code.</p>

<p>(Last edited on APR 26TH, 2014)</p>

<hr />

<div class="footnotes">
  <ol>
    <li id="fn:1">

      <p>Visual comparison between LaTeX and Word output (hyphenation,
typesetting, ligatures etc) on
<a href="http://tex.stackexchange.com/q/110133">$\rm \TeX$–$\rm \LaTeX$ Stack Exchange</a>. <a href="#fnref:1" class="reversefootnote">&#8617;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:2">

      <p>Taraborelli, D.  (July 4, 2011).  <em>The Beauty of $\rm \LaTeX$</em>.
Retrieved from <a href="http://nitens.org/taraborelli/latex">http://nitens.org/taraborelli/latex</a> <a href="#fnref:2" class="reversefootnote">&#8617;</a></p>
    </li>
  </ol>
</div>
]]></content>
    
